Mini Motor Racing managed to impress me right from the start with its slick visuals and amazing car physics. But what is this Mini Motor Racing anyway? Well, Mini Motor Racing is a top-down racer where you get to control a bunch of super deformed cars across a multitude of tracks. From beachheads, mountain tops, deserts, and all the way to neon cityscapes, the game offers beautiful vistas for the player to enjoy.       The tracks themselves can be quite tricky with narrow and difficult turns, which only  an agile and dedicated driver could ever hope to overcome. Fortunately, the exaggerated cars lend themselves perfectly to these twisty tracks. This is backed by an innovative control scheme in the form of an on-screen wheel that offers precise handling of these high-octane beasts. I wholeheartedly recommend this game, especially since it is not everyday that you find a high-quality title on the store.

This is an excellent game. I have played through the entire game and I still play it for fun.  The game has a few issues though. The first is minor but the game ignores its own in game SFX audio setting forcing you to use the OS volume if you don't want sound effects.   Secondly, in the later races, the AI suffers from what I call "designated winner" strategy. This is where the AI decides at the beginning of the race that one of the AI cars will be the winner and all of the other cars are on a mission to **** you up no matter if it costs them the race. This includes strategies like the ol' 4 cars holding you to a wall in the first turn while the designated winner gets 3/4ths a lap lead on you, knocking your car on its side then each car tapping you as they go by and each resetting your respawn timer while the designated winner takes a lap unobstructed, and my favorite the "designated winner has infinite nitro".  and last and possibly the most frustrating bug happens on a few levels, but its the worst on Cliffs (rev), there is a jump that lands right in front of the finish line. Sometimes instead of landing, your car just falls right through the map, respawns & losing the race

After playing for a couple of weeks, I suspect the game is fixed. Every 4-6 races, an AI opponent is added to the race who is faster than you and will inevitably beat you every time unless you upgrade your car. I suspect it takes you current car stats and makes the opponent better in on or two places (normally acceleration and top speed), forcing you to spend in-game currency on upgrades. I became sure in my suspicions when I upgraded my a race earlier than the 4-6 cycle, then next race found myself losing to another car (6 attempts). I accidentally upgraded twice within the same cycle and when I hit the "cheat" opponent I was unable to beat him (even though I'd upgraded twice recently). In short; THE GAME IS FIXED. Also,this cheat system means you can never afford one of the $15k cars with the game winnings, forcing players to purchase micro-transactions, even though the game isn't free to start with. I wouldn't be as annoyed with the fixing if I didn't have to pay for the app in the first place. The gameplay is fun, but I refuse to hand more money to a developer who uses these types of cheap tricks against their players.

The graphics are incredibly detailed and smooth on the G2 and it uses a very clever technique to keep the tracks interesting; as you advance, it reuses the same set of tracks but the camera angle changes, the direction of travel reverses from time to time, and the seasons and track conditions change to keep things entertaining and challenging.  It's like the same track is a new and different track; master one and you haven't mastered it from different views.  Awesome.  The other "computer" players are also very realistic in their moves and sometimes ruthlessness.  I love it!  Also, to those that complain about the controls... they are changeable and you can re-position them.  If you don't like the response or positioning of a set of controls, simply try another configuration.

Mini Motors is my current favorite game on Android and has been for several months. Really enjoying the recent holiday update and the Extended Championship. Glad to see more tracks and half-off the cars (temporarily, anyway) is great! Some of my favorite features:  * Head to head racing with a friend (my daughter loves this mode) * Lots of opportunity for upgrades and different user racing styles * Some really easy tracks and some tracks that are really challenging * Lots of different ways to configure steering and acceleration controls. Current favorite: directional wheel on the right (right thumb), accelerator on the right (right thumb) * Looks great on tablets.

My thoughts:  - Great graphics and style - Can be good fun at times - Can also be extremely annoying (and not in a 'lets play again' way - more a 'lets uninstall' way) - Hyper-aggressive CPU cars - Extremely twitchy player car - Turbo button stops working quite often - In game upgrades are priced excessively high, pushing the user towards IAP  Because it is so close to being great, the bad things seem even worse. It is hard to love this game.

The graphics are mostly beautiful. Sadly, this game gets buggier with every update, and the AI doesn't improve. It still has no real intelligence whatsoever, and spends all its time crashing into you--usually right after firing a nitro so you get flipped or spun. Since the last update, AI cars seem slightlly slower, but tracks are still  designed to hang up your car when rammed by the ruthless (and hopeless) AI, losing you more time. And the bugs... oh my goodness, the bugs. On top of the existing quirks -- steering that locks in one direction or other with no touch on the screen, a lap counter that occasionally counts down when you cross the finish line in the right direction, bonus items that register as the wrong thing, random stutter, and menus that freeze up for multiple seconds at a time -- there are now problems with huge portions of track being rendered completely without textures, too, making the game even harder to play. And the scoring system is clearly designed to force you to spend real money to "earn" cars and tracks. What should be a beautiful, really fun game is just painfully buggy and frustrating. I could cry for what this game could be, I really could.

I really like this game. I'm nearly done it. But so far though I haven't seen a reason to 3 star any race. But I am a little OCD so it becomes my goal. The cars you start off with aren't overly nice looking and it takes Way too long to get a better looking car unlocked.  The biggest problem I found was that your car would sometimes turn a 180 the wrong direction when you cross over the center pivot of the joystick. Being on a screen with no tactile feedback, it's quite easy to do.  Then there's the menu... It really does the most basic job at showing what buttons are. No visual extras like an animated shine or just a little movement. I find that when I'm choosing a race I have to press it several times. Maybe it's loading and doesn't change the screen, or there's some special area I need to touch. Then the WORST part about the menus. After you win a race you have to wait 5 seconds until the trophy shows up (it should be immediate). Then you must wait for the clapping before you can choose a level. But there is no visual indication that the game is "paused" during this. So you're left pressing and pressing on the next level over and over until the clapping is done. Bad beta testers.

In later race, the Computer cars appear to have infinite turbos.  So when you've used up all of your turbos desperately trying to gain an early lead, the computer cars will simply claw back whatever gap you've opened up by either using their infinite turbos or just being quicker than you - regardless of how much you've upgraded your car.  If you're out in front and you crash, the AI will then wait until everyone else catches up and then place you at the BACK of the grid, making it completely impossible to then win the race.  If you crash in to a wall (which happens frequently, it will keep you pinned there until the rest of the field catches up.  Often, in later races, the races themselves start to resemble a demolition derby with the computer cars spending most of the race ramming you as much as possible.  This creates scenarios where you are trying for DAYS to complete a SINGLE TRACK.  That's not playability, that's absurd !!.  I like the game, don't get me wrong, but the AI really does kill it a lot of the time - how i haven't thrown my phone across the room in utter, blind frustration i don't know.

I love this game. It is the best top-down racer I have played. Graphics are awesome and the controls are fantastic. The physics and handling are so fun. The AI is definitely tough and sometimes frustrating, but totally beatable if you take the time to really get comfortable with the game, learn the tracks, and work on perfecting your lines. I agree with others that the progression is a bit steep and it is definitely designed to get you to make in-app purchases to speed things up. This is the main reason it gets 4 instead of 5 stars. That being said, the game is worth a lot more than the price of entry so I didn't feel ripped off when I purchased the double-earnings booster for an extra buck. I highly recommend this option. I was able to fully upgrade my first car and beat the game with very little money grinding after buying that addon. I was then able to pretty quickly save up to buy and max out the formula car to complete the second championship and go back and get gold on the handful of races from the first championship that were a bit too hard. The game is such a joy to play that I never felt like I was having to grind to progress. Looking forward to new chamionships!
